<h2>Grouping Content</h2>
<h3>Paragraphs and Blockquotes</h3>
<p>Paragraphs are wrapped in <code>&lt;p&gt;</code> tags to denote paragraph text. If a paragraph is directly quoted from elsewhere, it gets wrapped in a <code>&lt;blockquote&gt;</code> element, like so:</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>All this happened, more or less. The war parts, anyway, are pretty much true. One guy I knew really <em>was</em> show in Dresden for taking a teapot that wasn't his. Another guy I knew really <em>did</em> threaten to have his personal enemies killed by hired gunmen after the war. And so on. I've changed all the names.</p>
  <p>—<cite>Slaughterhouse Five</cite>, by Kurt Vonnegut</p>
</blockquote>
<p>As above, citations should be attributed whenever possible using <code>&lt;cite&gt;</code> tags around the title of the quoted work.</p>
<h3>Lists</h3>
<p>Lists that are in no particular order should be marked up with <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code> tags. Unordered lists can of course be nested within each other, like so:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Animals</li>
  <li>Vegetables
    <ul>
      <li>Lettuce</li>
      <li>Carrots</li>
      <li>Zucchini</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Minerals</li>
</ul>
<p>Lists that are ordered—perhaps chronologically or hierarchically—should be marked up with <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code> tags, which may also be nested.</p>
<ol>
  <li>Tomorrow</li>
  <li>Today
    <ol>
      <li>An hour from now</li>
      <li>Right now</li>
      <li>An hour ago</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li>Yesterday</li>
</ol>
<p>Another kind of list is a description list, which is a list of items with one or more descriptions of them, such as in a glossary. The entire list should be wrapped in <code>&lt;dl&gt;</code> tags, with terms in <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> tags and descriptions in <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> tags, like so:</p>
<dl>
  <dt>The Internet</dt>
  <dd>An vast and complicated network of computers developed over decades to facilitate the dissemination of cat pictures.</dd>
  <dd>A series of tubes. (As here, one term can have multiple definitions.)</dd>
  <dt>Another term</dt>
  <dd>I'm not defining this (As you can see, simply marking up something as a description doesn't guarantee that it will cooperate.)</dd>
</dl>
<h2>Figures</h2>
<p>Figures are graphics referenced within a body of text. A figure is marked up predictably with the <code>&lt;figure&gt;</code> element, which may contain a <code>&lt;figcaption&gt;</code> element to name or explain the illustration.</p>
<figure>
  <%= image_tag "figure.png", title: "an example of a figure image" %>
  <figcaption>Figures are often images. This figure uses the default styling, which is to span the full width of the text column.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>One might also wish to float a figure off to the side of the body text. The next example accomplishes this by adding a class of "left" to the figure.</p>
<figure class="left">
  <%= image_tag "figure.png", title: "an example of a figure image" %>
  <figcaption>This figure has a class of "left".</figcaption>
</figure>
